{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012zEZwQ28vbdnie9X9L3kaP","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→stepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4]\n     3→inputDocuments:\n     4→  - _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/tech-spec-multi-stack-support.md\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→# Multi-Stack Project Support - Epic Breakdown\n     8→\n     9→## Overview\n    10→\n    11→This document provides the complete epic and story breakdown for adding multi-stack project support to codeharness, enabling monorepo projects with multiple languages to get full harness features for all stacks.\n    12→\n    13→## Requirements Inventory\n    14→\n    15→### Functional Requirements\n    16→\n    17→FR1: System detects all stack markers at project root (not early-return)\n    18→FR2: System scans immediate subdirectories for stack markers (monorepo layout)\n    19→FR3: System returns `StackDetection[]` with stack name + directory for each detected stack\n    20→FR4: System migrates state from `stack: string | null` to `stacks: string[]` with backward compat\n    21→FR5: System runs coverage detection per-stack independently\n    22→FR6: System installs OTLP packages per-stack independently\n    23→FR7: System generates multi-stage Dockerfile composing build stages for all detected stacks\n    24→FR8: System generates combined AGENTS.md listing all stacks with per-stack build/test commands\n    25→\n    26→### NonFunctional Requirements\n    27→\n    28→NFR1: No file exceeds 300 lines\n    29→NFR2: Zero regressions on existing single-stack tests\n    30→NFR3: No new npm dependencies\n    31→NFR4: `detectStack()` compat wrapper and `state.stack` field preserved — no breaking changes\n    32→\n    33→### Additional Requirements\n    34→\n    35→- Subdirectory scan skips `node_modules`, `.git`, `target`, `__pycache__`, `dist`, `build`, `coverage`\n    36→- Detection order: root stacks first (nodejs > python > rust), then subdir stacks alphabetically\n    37→- Single-stack output must be identical to current templates (no visual regression)\n    38→\n    39→### FR Coverage Map\n    40→\n    41→| FR | Epic | Story |\n    42→|----|------|-------|\n    43→| FR1, FR2, FR3 | Epic 1 | 9-1 |\n    44→| FR4 | Epic 1 | 9-2 |\n    45→| FR5, FR6 | Epic 2 | 9-3 |\n    46→| FR7 | Epic 2 | 9-4 |\n    47→| FR8 | Epic 2 | 9-5 |\n    48→\n    49→## Epic List\n    50→\n    51→- **Epic 1: Multi-Stack Detection & State** — Detect multiple stacks, subdir scanning, state migration\n    52→- **Epic 2: Multi-Stack Consumers** — Per-stack init orchestration, multi-stage Dockerfile, combined docs\n    53→\n    54→## Epic 1: Multi-Stack Detection & State\n    55→\n    56→Enable codeharness to detect all stacks in a project (root and subdirectories) and store them in state with backward compatibility.\n    57→\n    58→### Story 9-1: Multi-stack detection with subdirectory scanning\n    59→\n    60→As a developer with a monorepo containing multiple languages,\n    61→I want codeharness to detect all stacks in my project,\n    62→So that every language gets harness features instead of just the first detected.\n    63→\n    64→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    65→\n    66→**Given** a project with `package.json` AND `Cargo.toml` at root\n    67→**When** `detectStacks()` is called\n    68→**Then** it returns `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: '.' }, { stack: 'rust', dir: '.' }]`\n    69→\n    70→**Given** a monorepo with `frontend/package.json` and `backend/Cargo.toml`\n    71→**When** `detectStacks()` is called\n    72→**Then** it returns `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: 'frontend' }, { stack: 'rust', dir: 'backend' }]`\n    73→\n    74→**Given** a single-stack project with only `package.json`\n    75→**When** `detectStacks()` is called\n    76→**Then** it returns `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: '.' }]`\n    77→**And** `detectStack()` compat wrapper returns `'nodejs'`\n    78→\n    79→**Given** an empty directory\n    80→**When** `detectStacks()` is called\n    81→**Then** it returns `[]`\n    82→**And** `detectStack()` compat wrapper returns `null`\n    83→\n    84→**Given** a project with `node_modules/some-package/Cargo.toml`\n    85→**When** `detectStacks()` scans subdirectories\n    86→**Then** `node_modules` is skipped (no false positive)\n    87→\n    88→**Given** root has `package.json` and subdir `api/` has `Cargo.toml`\n    89→**When** `detectStacks()` is called\n    90→**Then** root stacks appear first, subdir stacks after, sorted alphabetically by dir name\n    91→\n    92→### Story 9-2: State schema migration for multi-stack\n    93→\n    94→As a developer upgrading codeharness,\n    95→I want my existing state file to auto-migrate to the new multi-stack format,\n    96→So that I don't have to re-initialize.\n    97→\n    98→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    99→\n   100→**Given** an old state file with `stack: 'nodejs'`\n   101→**When** `readState()` is called\n   102→**Then** `state.stacks` is `['nodejs']` and `state.stack` is `'nodejs'`\n   103→\n   104→**Given** a new state file with `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']`\n   105→**When** `readState()` is called\n   106→**Then** `state.stacks` is `['nodejs', 'rust']` and `state.stack` is `'nodejs'`\n   107→\n   108→**Given** a state file with neither `stack` nor `stacks`\n   109→**When** `readState()` is called\n   110→**Then** `state.stacks` is `[]` and `state.stack` is `null`\n   111→\n   112→**Given** state is written via `writeState()`\n   113→**When** the file is inspected\n   114→**Then** it contains both `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']` AND `stack: 'nodejs'` for backward compat\n   115→\n   116→## Epic 2: Multi-Stack Consumers\n   117→\n   118→Update init orchestration, Dockerfile generation, and docs scaffolding to handle multiple stacks.\n   119→\n   120→### Story 9-3: Init orchestrator per-stack iteration\n   121→\n   122→As a developer running `codeharness init` on a multi-stack project,\n   123→I want coverage and OTLP to be configured for each detected stack,\n   124→So that all languages get observability and test coverage.\n   125→\n   126→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   127→\n   128→**Given** a multi-stack project (nodejs + rust)\n   129→**When** `codeharness init` runs\n   130→**Then** coverage tools are detected for each stack independently (c8 for nodejs, cargo-tarpaulin for rust)\n   131→\n   132→**Given** a multi-stack project (nodejs + rust)\n   133→**When** `codeharness init` runs\n   134→**Then** OTLP packages are installed for each stack independently (npm packages for nodejs, cargo crates for rust)\n   135→\n   136→**Given** a multi-stack project\n   137→**When** `codeharness init` runs\n   138→**Then** info messages list all detected stacks (e.g., `Stack detected: Node.js (package.json) + Rust (Cargo.toml)`)\n   139→\n   140→**Given** a multi-stack project\n   141→**When** state is created\n   142→**Then** `state.stacks` contains all detected stack names and `state.app_type` reflects primary stack\n   143→\n   144→### Story 9-4: Multi-stage Dockerfile generation\n   145→\n   146→As a developer deploying a multi-stack project,\n   147→I want a single Dockerfile with build stages for each stack,\n   148→So that all components are built and packaged together.\n   149→\n   150→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   151→\n   152→**Given** a multi-stack project (nodejs + rust)\n   153→**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   154→**Then** it produces a multi-stage Dockerfile with `node:22-slim` AND `rust:1.82-slim` build stages and a combined `debian:bookworm-slim` runtime stage\n   155→\n   156→**Given** a single-stack project\n   157→**When** `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called\n   158→**Then** output is identical to the current single-stack template (no regression)\n   159→\n   160→**Given** a multi-stack Dockerfile\n   161→**When** inspected\n   162→**Then** each build stage is named `build-{stack}` and the runtime stage copies from all build stages\n   163→\n   164→### Story 9-5: Multi-stack docs and remaining consumers\n   165→\n   166→As a developer initializing a multi-stack project,\n   167→I want AGENTS.md and README to reflect all detected stacks,\n   168→So that AI agents and humans know how to build/test all components.\n   169→\n   170→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   171→\n   172→**Given** a multi-stack project\n   173→**When** `generateAgentsMdContent()` is called\n   174→**Then** it lists build/test commands for all detected stacks\n   175→\n   176→**Given** `['nodejs', 'rust']`\n   177→**When** `getStackLabel()` is called\n   178→**Then** it returns `'Node.js (package.json) + Rust (Cargo.toml)'`\n   179→\n   180→**Given** a multi-stack project\n   181→**When** `getProjectName()` is called\n   182→**Then** it tries each stack's project file (package.json name, Cargo.toml [package] name) and returns the first found\n   183→\n   184→**Given** state has `stacks: ['nodejs', 'rust']`\n   185→**When** `verify/env.ts` checks for nodejs\n   186→**Then** it uses `stacks.includes('nodejs')` instead of `stack === 'nodejs'`\n   187→\n   188→**Given** all changes complete\n   189→**When** `npm test` runs\n   190→**Then** all existing single-stack tests pass with 0 regressions\n   191→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Du6Dm3wXgPT4dCoQ6SefyL","session_id":"e8d3a9d7-303a-4d24-9a07-31410ec54173","uuid":"f3702cfd-5736-444f-a79c-d3a0dacd30c1","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:13:22.421Z"}
