{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01ScmsMcWUP9iSnvx1qYW1h8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EPP3ZdDzYq8bWwQERGph7q","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/tech-spec-multi-stack-support.md","offset":80},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2440,"cache_read_input_tokens":46829,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2440,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Du6Dm3wXgPT4dCoQ6SefyL","session_id":"e8d3a9d7-303a-4d24-9a07-31410ec54173","uuid":"11696ae1-4800-4ab9-8f20-c932b26ee7b0"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EPP3ZdDzYq8bWwQERGph7q","type":"tool_result","content":"    80→| `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` | `generateDockerfileTemplate()` L112 | New: `generateMultiStackDockerfile(stacks[])`. Composes per-stack build stages + combined runtime. |\n    81→| `src/modules/infra/docs-scaffold.ts` | `getStackLabel()` L50, `generateAgentsMdContent()` L63 | New overloads accepting `string[]`. Concat labels, concat build commands. |\n    82→| `src/modules/infra/init-project.ts` | `initProjectInner()` L51-162 | Core orchestrator: L68 `detectStack()` → `detectStacks()`. Loop over results for coverage, OTLP, app type. State gets `stacks[]`. |\n    83→| `src/modules/infra/types.ts` | `InitResult` L65, L77 | `stack: string \\| null` → `stacks: string[]`. Keep `stack` as getter alias. |\n    84→| `src/modules/verify/env.ts` | Stack checks | Update to check `stacks.includes()` instead of `=== 'nodejs'`. |\n    85→| `src/commands/teardown.ts` | Stack reference | Minor — reads from state, uses primary stack. |\n    86→| `src/templates/readme.ts` | `getInstallCommand()` L72 | Accept `string[]`, render per-stack install commands. |\n    87→\n    88→### Technical Decisions\n    89→\n    90→- **New type:** `StackDetection = { stack: string; dir: string }` — `dir` is the directory where the stack marker was found (root or subdirectory).\n    91→- **Return type:** `detectStacks()` returns `StackDetection[]` (empty = no stack detected). Keep `detectStack()` as compat wrapper returning `stacks[0]?.stack ?? null`.\n    92→- **Subdirectory scanning:** Use `readdirSync(dir, { withFileTypes: true })` to list immediate children. For each directory child, check for stack markers. Skip `node_modules`, `.git`, `target`, `__pycache__`, `dist`, `build`.\n    93→- **Primary stack:** `stacks[0]` is primary. Detection order: root-level stacks first (nodejs > python > rust), then subdirectory stacks sorted alphabetically by dir name.\n    94→- **State migration:** New field `stacks: string[]`. `readState()` checks: if `stacks` exists, use it. If only `stack` exists (old format), convert to `stacks: [stack]`. `writeState()` always writes `stacks`. Keep `stack` field for backward compat = `stacks[0] ?? null`.\n    95→- **Coverage:** `init-project.ts` iterates `stacks` and calls `detectCoverageTool(dir)` per stack. `coverage.ts` internals unchanged — they already detect stack from the dir they're given.\n    96→- **OTLP:** `init-project.ts` iterates `stacks` and calls `instrumentProject(stackDir, stack)` per stack. Env vars shared (same endpoint/service name).\n    97→- **Dockerfile:** New `generateMultiStackDockerfile(detections: StackDetection[])` composes stages. If single stack, output identical to current templates. If multi-stack, one build stage per stack + combined runtime.\n    98→- **Docs:** `generateAgentsMdContent()` accepts `StackDetection[]`. Lists all stacks with per-stack build/test commands. `getStackLabel()` accepts `string[]` and joins with ` + `.\n    99→- **App type:** Per-stack. `detectAppType()` called for each stack independently. State stores `app_types: Record<string, AppType>` alongside primary `app_type: stacks[0]'s type`.\n   100→- **Minimal API surface change strategy:** Most consumers (`coverage.ts`, `otlp.ts`, `dockerfile-template.ts`) keep their single-stack signatures. The orchestrator (`init-project.ts`) loops over stacks. This minimizes blast radius — only the orchestrator and state/detection layers change significantly.\n   101→\n   102→## Implementation Plan\n   103→\n   104→### Tasks\n   105→\n   106→Tasks ordered by dependency — core types first, then detection, then consumers.\n   107→\n   108→- [ ] Task 1: Define `StackDetection` type and update `detectStack()`\n   109→  - File: `src/lib/stack-detect.ts`\n   110→  - Action: Add `export interface StackDetection { stack: string; dir: string; }`. Create `detectStacks(dir)` that: (1) checks root for all stack markers (not early-return), collecting all matches; (2) scans immediate subdirectories (skip `node_modules`, `.git`, `target`, `__pycache__`, `dist`, `build`, `coverage`) for stack markers; (3) returns `StackDetection[]` ordered: root stacks first (nodejs > python > rust), then subdir stacks sorted by dir name. Keep `detectStack()` as compat wrapper: `return detectStacks(dir)[0]?.stack ?? null`.\n   111→  - Notes: Use `readdirSync(dir, { withFileTypes: true })` for subdir scan. Filter `dirent.isDirectory()`. Root detection collects ALL matches (remove early returns).\n   112→\n   113→- [ ] Task 2: Update state schema and migration\n   114→  - File: `src/lib/state.ts`\n   115→  - Action: Add `stacks: string[]` to `HarnessState`. Keep `stack: string | null` as deprecated compat field. In `readState()`: if `stacks` exists use it; if only `stack` exists convert `[stack]`; if neither, `[]`. In `writeState()`: always write `stacks`, also write `stack: stacks[0] ?? null` for compat. Update `getDefaultState()` to accept `string[]`.\n   116→  - Notes: This is the migration path. Old state files with `stack: 'nodejs'` auto-upgrade to `stacks: ['nodejs']`.\n   117→\n   118→- [ ] Task 3: Update init orchestrator to loop over stacks\n   119→  - File: `src/modules/infra/init-project.ts`\n   120→  - Action: L68: replace `detectStack(projectDir)` with `detectStacks(projectDir)`. Store `StackDetection[]`. Iterate for: app type detection (per-stack), coverage tool (per-stack using detection.dir), OTLP instrumentation (per-stack using detection.dir). Pass primary stack to Dockerfile generation. Update state creation: `state.stacks = detections.map(d => d.stack)`, `state.stack = stacks[0] ?? null`. Update info messages to list all detected stacks.\n   121→  - Notes: This is the main orchestration change. Coverage and OTLP internals stay single-stack — only the loop changes.\n   122→\n   123→- [ ] Task 4: Update `InitResult` and infra types\n   124→  - File: `src/modules/infra/types.ts`\n   125→  - Action: Change `stack: string | null` to `stacks: string[]` in `InitResult`. Keep `stack` as computed getter or set to `stacks[0] ?? null`. Update `dockerfile` type if needed.\n   126→\n   127→- [ ] Task 5: Multi-stack Dockerfile generation\n   128→  - File: `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts`\n   129→  - Action: Add `generateMultiStackDockerfile(detections: StackDetection[]): string` that composes build stages from existing per-stack templates. Single stack = identical to current output. Multi-stack = one `FROM ... AS build-{stack}` per stack + combined `FROM debian:bookworm-slim` runtime copying from all build stages. Update `generateDockerfileTemplate()` to accept `StackDetection[]` and delegate.\n   130→  - Notes: Reuse existing `nodejsTemplate()`, `pythonTemplate()`, `rustTemplate()` as building blocks. Extract build vs runtime sections.\n   131→\n   132→- [ ] Task 6: Multi-stack docs scaffolding\n   133→  - File: `src/modules/infra/docs-scaffold.ts`\n   134→  - Action: Update `getStackLabel()` to accept `string | string[]` — if array, join with ` + ` (e.g., `Node.js + Rust`). Update `getCoverageTool()` to accept `string | string[]` — if array, return primary stack's tool. Update `generateAgentsMdContent()` to accept `string | StackDetection[]` — if array, list build/test commands for each stack. Update `getProjectName()` — try each stack's project file.\n   135→  - Notes: Overloaded signatures maintain backward compat for existing callers.\n   136→\n   137→- [ ] Task 7: Update remaining consumers\n   138→  - Files: `src/modules/verify/env.ts`, `src/commands/teardown.ts`, `src/templates/readme.ts`\n   139→  - Action: `verify/env.ts`: change `state.stack === 'nodejs'` to `state.stacks?.includes('nodejs')`. `teardown.ts`: read `stacks` from state, use primary for any stack-specific cleanup. `readme.ts`: accept `string[]`, render per-stack install commands.\n   140→  - Notes: Minor changes — these files have 1-2 stack references each.\n   141→\n   142→- [ ] Task 8: Tests for all changes\n   143→  - Files: `src/lib/__tests__/stack-detect.test.ts`, `src/lib/__tests__/state.test.ts`, `src/modules/infra/__tests__/init-project.test.ts`, `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts`, `src/modules/infra/__tests__/docs-scaffold.test.ts`\n   144→  - Action: Add multi-stack test cases: (1) root with `package.json` + `Cargo.toml` → detects both; (2) monorepo `frontend/package.json` + `backend/Cargo.toml` → detects both with correct dirs; (3) single-stack backward compat — all existing tests pass unchanged; (4) state migration — old `stack` field auto-converts to `stacks`; (5) multi-stack Dockerfile — multiple build stages; (6) multi-stack AGENTS.md — lists all stacks; (7) empty dir → `[]` not `null`.\n   145→  - Notes: Use `vi.mock('node:fs')` to simulate monorepo directory structures. Create fixtures for various layouts.\n   146→\n   147→### Acceptance Criteria\n   148→\n   149→- [ ] AC1: Given a project with `package.json` AND `Cargo.toml` at root, when `detectStacks()` is called, then it returns `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: '.' }, { stack: 'rust', dir: '.' }]`\n   150→- [ ] AC2: Given a monorepo with `frontend/package.json` and `backend/Cargo.toml`, when `detectStacks()` is called, then it returns `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: 'frontend' }, { stack: 'rust', dir: 'backend' }]`\n   151→- [ ] AC3: Given a single-stack project with only `package.json`, when `detectStacks()` is called, then it returns `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: '.' }]` and `detectStack()` returns `'nodejs'`\n   152→- [ ] AC4: Given an empty directory, when `detectStacks()` is called, then it returns `[]` and `detectStack()` returns `null`\n   153→- [ ] AC5: Given an old state file with `stack: 'nodejs'`, when `readState()` is called, then `state.stacks` is `['nodejs']` and `state.stack` is `'nodejs'`\n   154→- [ ] AC6: Given a multi-stack project, when `codeharness init` runs, then coverage tools are detected for each stack independently\n   155→- [ ] AC7: Given a multi-stack project, when `codeharness init` runs, then OTLP packages are installed for each stack independently\n   156→- [ ] AC8: Given a multi-stack project (nodejs + rust), when `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called, then it produces a multi-stage Dockerfile with both `node:22-slim` and `rust:1.82-slim` build stages\n   157→- [ ] AC9: Given a single-stack project, when `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called, then output is identical to current single-stack template (no regression)\n   158→- [ ] AC10: Given a multi-stack project, when `generateAgentsMdContent()` is called, then it lists build/test commands for all detected stacks\n   159→- [ ] AC11: Given a multi-stack project, when `getStackLabel()` is called with `['nodejs', 'rust']`, then it returns `'Node.js (package.json) + Rust (Cargo.toml)'`\n   160→- [ ] AC12: Given all changes, when `npm test` runs, then all existing single-stack tests pass with 0 regressions\n   161→\n   162→## Additional Context\n   163→\n   164→### Dependencies\n   165→\n   166→- No new npm dependencies. Uses `readdirSync` from `node:fs` (already imported).\n   167→- No changes to the CLI interface — `codeharness init` works the same, just detects more.\n   168→\n   169→### Testing Strategy\n   170→\n   171→- **Unit tests:** Mock `readdirSync` and `existsSync` to simulate monorepo layouts. Test detection ordering (root first, then subdirs). Test state migration (old → new format). Test single-stack backward compat exhaustively.\n   172→- **Integration tests:** None required — init pipeline integration is already tested.\n   173→- **Manual testing:** Create a real monorepo (`mkdir -p frontend backend && cd frontend && npm init -y && cd ../backend && cargo init`) and run `codeharness init`.\n   174→- **Regression safety:** All existing single-stack tests must pass unchanged. `detectStack()` wrapper ensures callers that haven't migrated still work.\n   175→\n   176→### Notes\n   177→\n   178→- **Blast radius is small:** Only 3 files change significantly (stack-detect, state, init-project). The other 8 files have 1-3 line changes each. Coverage, OTLP, and Dockerfile internals stay single-stack.\n   179→- **No breaking changes:** `detectStack()` still works. `HarnessState.stack` still works. Old state files auto-migrate. This is purely additive.\n   180→- **Future: per-subdir config.** If users want different coverage targets or OTLP endpoints per stack, that's a future feature. For now, harness-level config applies to all stacks.\n   181→- **Subdir skip list is important:** Must skip `node_modules`, `.git`, `target`, etc. to avoid false positives (e.g., `node_modules/some-package/Cargo.toml`).\n   182→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Du6Dm3wXgPT4dCoQ6SefyL","session_id":"e8d3a9d7-303a-4d24-9a07-31410ec54173","uuid":"199cea6a-d66a-40e7-a3b3-58e9d65edee5","timestamp":"2026-03-23T15:14:03.446Z"}
