{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01M8MKFNzRpiji4k7VVgQ3GK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 9.4: Multi-stage Dockerfile generation\n     2→\n     3→Status: review\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As a developer deploying a multi-stack project,\n    10→I want a single Dockerfile with build stages for each stack,\n    11→So that all components are built and packaged together.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→- [x] AC1: Given a multi-stack project (nodejs + rust), when `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called with `StackDetection[]`, then it produces a multi-stage Dockerfile with a `FROM node:22-slim AS build-nodejs` stage AND a `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS build-rust` stage and a combined `FROM debian:bookworm-slim` runtime stage <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→- [x] AC2: Given a single-stack project, when `generateDockerfileTemplate()` is called with a single-element `StackDetection[]`, then output is byte-identical to the current single-stack template (no regression) <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→- [x] AC3: Given a multi-stack Dockerfile, when inspected, then each build stage is named `build-{stack}` (e.g., `build-nodejs`, `build-rust`) and the runtime stage uses `COPY --from=build-{stack}` to copy artifacts from all build stages <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→- [x] AC4: Given a multi-stack Dockerfile, when `validateDockerfile()` is run against it, then it passes all 6 rule categories (pinned FROM, non-root USER, curl/jq utilities, cache cleanup, section comments, WORKDIR) <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→- [x] AC5: Given the orchestrator in `init-project.ts` calls `generateDockerfileTemplate()`, when a multi-stack project is initialized, then the function receives the full `StackDetection[]` (not just primary stack) and writes a multi-stage Dockerfile <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→- [x] AC6: Given all changes complete, when `npm test` runs, then all existing single-stack Dockerfile tests pass with zero regressions <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→\n    22→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    23→\n    24→- [x] Task 1: Update `generateDockerfileTemplate()` signature (AC: #1, #2, #5)\n    25→  - [x] 1.1 Change second parameter from `stack: string | null` to accept `StackDetection[]` OR keep backward-compat overload accepting `string | null` — distinguish at runtime: if second arg is an array, use multi-stack path; if string/null, use existing single-stack path\n    26→  - [x] 1.2 Import `StackDetection` type from `../../lib/stack-detect.js`\n    27→  - [x] 1.3 Update `DockerfileTemplateResult` to include `stacks: string[]` alongside existing `stack: string`\n    28→- [x] Task 2: Add multi-stage Dockerfile composition logic (AC: #1, #3)\n    29→  - [x] 2.1 Create `multiStageTemplate(detections: StackDetection[]): string` that composes per-stack build stages + combined runtime\n    30→  - [x] 2.2 Extract build-stage content from existing `nodejsTemplate()`, `pythonTemplate()`, `rustTemplate()` — each becomes a named `AS build-{stack}` stage\n    31→  - [x] 2.3 Generate combined `FROM debian:bookworm-slim` runtime stage that: installs curl/jq, copies artifacts from all build stages via `COPY --from=build-{stack}`, sets `USER nobody`, sets `WORKDIR /workspace`\n    32→  - [x] 2.4 Route: if `detections.length === 1`, delegate to existing single-stack template function (preserving byte-identical output); if `>1`, use multi-stage composition\n    33→- [x] Task 3: Update `init-project.ts` to pass `StackDetection[]` (AC: #5)\n    34→  - [x] 3.1 Change L87 `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir, stack)` to pass `allStacks` (the `StackDetection[]` from `detectStacks()`)\n    35→  - [x] 3.2 Update result handling: `result.dockerfile = { generated: true, stack: dfResult.data.stack }` may need `stacks` field\n    36→- [x] Task 4: Ensure `validateDockerfile()` passes on multi-stage output (AC: #4)\n    37→  - [x] 4.1 Verify multi-stage Dockerfile satisfies all 6 validation rule categories (pinned FROM tags, non-root USER, curl/jq, cache cleanup, comments, WORKDIR)\n    38→  - [x] 4.2 If validator chokes on multiple FROM lines, adjust validation logic to handle multi-stage builds\n    39→- [x] Task 5: Add tests for multi-stage generation (AC: #1, #3, #6)\n    40→  - [x] 5.1 Test: nodejs+rust detections → output contains `FROM node:22-slim AS build-nodejs`, `FROM rust:1.82-slim AS build-rust`, `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`\n    41→  - [x] 5.2 Test: nodejs+rust → output contains `COPY --from=build-nodejs` and `COPY --from=build-rust`\n    42→  - [x] 5.3 Test: nodejs+rust → runtime stage has curl, jq, `USER nobody`, `WORKDIR /workspace`\n    43→  - [x] 5.4 Test: nodejs+python+rust (3 stacks) → all 3 build stages present\n    44→  - [x] 5.5 Test: single-stack `[{ stack: 'nodejs', dir: '.' }]` → output identical to `generateDockerfileTemplate('/project', 'nodejs')` (backward compat)\n    45→  - [x] 5.6 Test: single-stack rust `[{ stack: 'rust', dir: '.' }]` → output identical to current rust template\n    46→  - [x] 5.7 Test: multi-stage Dockerfile passes `validateDockerfile()`\n    47→  - [x] 5.8 Test: backward-compat string argument still works (pass `'nodejs'` not array)\n    48→- [x] Task 6: Verify backward compat and regressions (AC: #2, #6)\n    49→  - [x] 6.1 Run full test suite — all existing dockerfile-template tests pass unchanged\n    50→  - [x] 6.2 Verify init-project tests still pass with updated call signature\n    51→\n    52→## Dev Notes\n    53→\n    54→### Architecture & Key Patterns\n    55→\n    56→- **Result\\<T\\> pattern:** All public functions return `Result<T>` using `ok()` / `fail()` from `../../types/result.js`. Do not throw.\n    57→- **File limit:** <300 lines per file. Current `dockerfile-template.ts` is 149 lines. Multi-stage logic should fit within limit. If it approaches 300, extract a helper file.\n    58→- **Module boundary:** `dockerfile-template.ts` exports via `src/modules/infra/index.ts`. Any new exports must be added there.\n    59→- **Minimal API surface change:** Per tech spec, the orchestrator (`init-project.ts`) is the only significant caller. Internal template functions stay single-stack. The multi-stage composition reuses existing template content.\n    60→\n    61→### Current Code (as of story 9-3)\n    62→\n    63→**`src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts`** — 149 lines. Contains:\n    64→- `nodejsTemplate()`, `pythonTemplate()`, `rustTemplate()`, `genericTemplate()` — private functions returning Dockerfile content strings\n    65→- `generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir: string, stack: string | null): Result<DockerfileTemplateResult>` — checks if Dockerfile exists, selects template by stack, writes file\n    66→- The rust template already uses multi-stage build (`FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder` + `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`)\n    67→- `DockerfileTemplateResult = { path: string; stack: string }`\n    68→\n    69→**`src/modules/infra/init-project.ts` L86-93** — Current call:\n    70→```ts\n    71→const dfResult = generateDockerfileTemplate(projectDir, stack);\n    72→```\n    73→The `allStacks` variable (`StackDetection[]`) is available at L70:\n    74→```ts\n    75→const allStacks = detectStacks(projectDir);\n    76→```\n    77→Change L87 to pass `allStacks` instead of `stack`.\n    78→\n    79→**`src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts`** — Validates against 6 rule categories. Check that it handles multiple FROM lines (multi-stage builds). The pinned-FROM check must verify ALL FROM lines are pinned, not just the first.\n    80→\n    81→### Design Decisions\n    82→\n    83→1. **Single-stack routing:** When `detections.length === 1`, call the existing single-stack template function directly. This guarantees byte-identical output — zero regression risk.\n    84→2. **Backward compat overload:** Accept both `(projectDir, stack: string | null)` and `(projectDir, detections: StackDetection[])`. Detect at runtime: `Array.isArray(second)` → multi-stack path. This keeps all 430 lines of existing tests working without modification.\n    85→3. **Multi-stage composition:** Each stack contributes a named build stage. The runtime stage is `debian:bookworm-slim` (same as current rust runtime).\n    86→4. **Build stage naming:** `build-{stack}` — e.g., `build-nodejs`, `build-rust`, `build-python`. NOT `builder` (which the current rust template uses).\n    87→5. **Runtime stage content:** `FROM debian:bookworm-slim` → install curl/jq → `COPY --from=build-{stack}` for each → `USER nobody` → `WORKDIR /workspace`.\n    88→\n    89→### Important: Rust template already IS multi-stage\n    90→\n    91→The existing `rustTemplate()` returns a 2-stage Dockerfile (`FROM rust:1.82-slim AS builder` + `FROM debian:bookworm-slim`). For multi-stack, the rust build stage needs its AS name changed to `build-rust`. The runtime stage is shared. When extracting build-stage content, strip the runtime portion from the rust template.\n    92→\n    93→### Multi-stage Dockerfile structure\n    94→\n    95→```dockerfile\n    96→# === Build stage: nodejs ===\n    97→FROM node:22-slim AS build-nodejs\n    98→WORKDIR /build\n    99→COPY package*.json ./\n   100→RUN npm ci --production\n   101→COPY . .\n   102→\n   103→# === Build stage: rust ===\n   104→FROM rust:1.82-slim AS build-rust\n   105→WORKDIR /build\n   106→COPY . .\n   107→RUN cargo build --release\n   108→\n   109→# === Runtime stage ===\n   110→FROM debian:bookworm-slim\n   111→\n   112→# System utilities for verification\n   113→RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends curl jq && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n   114→\n   115→# Install artifacts from build stages\n   116→COPY --from=build-nodejs /build/node_modules ./node_modules\n   117→COPY --from=build-nodejs /build/ ./app/\n   118→COPY --from=build-rust /build/target/release/myapp /usr/local/bin/myapp\n   119→\n   120→# Run as non-root user\n   121→USER nobody\n   122→\n   123→WORKDIR /workspace\n   124→```\n   125→\n   126→### `validateDockerfile()` considerations\n   127→\n   128→Read `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` before implementing. The validator checks:\n   129→- Pinned FROM tags — multi-stage has multiple FROMs, ALL must be pinned (no `:latest`)\n   130→- Non-root USER — runtime stage must set this\n   131→- curl/jq utilities — runtime stage must install them\n   132→- Cache cleanup (`rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`) — each `apt-get` needs it\n   133→- Section comments — `#` comments present\n   134→- WORKDIR set\n   135→\n   136→If the validator regex matches only the first FROM or assumes a single FROM, it needs updating. Check the actual implementation before deciding.\n   137→\n   138→### Previous Story Intelligence (9-3)\n   139→\n   140→- `getStackLabel()` already accepts `string | string[] | null` — no changes needed\n   141→- Per-stack loops in init-project.ts follow pattern: `for (const detection of allStacks) { ... }`\n   142→- `allStacks` variable available at L70 in init-project.ts\n   143→- Code review found: dead code (results computed but unused), wrong matching (stack name vs dir). Verify all generated output is actually consumed.\n   144→- `state.coverage.tools` stores per-stack data — follow same pattern if per-stack Dockerfile info needed\n   145→- Test count: 3109 tests pass, 97.03% coverage after story 9-3\n   146→\n   147→### Files to Change\n   148→\n   149→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` — Add multi-stage composition, update signature to accept `StackDetection[]`, keep backward-compat for string arg\n   150→- `src/modules/infra/init-project.ts` — Change L87 to pass `allStacks` instead of `stack`\n   151→- `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts` — Add multi-stage tests (multi-stack output, single-stack no-regression, stage naming, COPY --from, validation compliance)\n   152→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` — Possibly update for multi-stage awareness (multiple FROM lines)\n   153→- `src/modules/infra/index.ts` — Add any new exports if needed\n   154→\n   155→### References\n   156→\n   157→- [Source: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/tech-spec-multi-stack-support.md — Task 5, AC8-AC9]\n   158→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-multi-stack-support.md — Story 9-4]\n   159→- [Source: src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts — current implementation, 149 lines]\n   160→- [Source: src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts — 430 lines, existing tests]\n   161→- [Source: src/modules/infra/init-project.ts L86-93 — Dockerfile generation call site]\n   162→- [Source: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/9-3-init-orchestrator-per-stack-iteration.md — previous story learnings]\n   163→\n   164→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   165→## Verification Requirements\n   166→\n   167→- [x] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/9-4-multi-stage-dockerfile-generation.proof.md`)\n   168→- [x] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   169→- [x] Test coverage meets target (100%)\n   170→\n   171→## Documentation Requirements\n   172→\n   173→- [x] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated (list modules touched)\n   174→- [x] Exec-plan created in `docs/exec-plans/active/9-4-multi-stage-dockerfile-generation.md`\n   175→\n   176→## Testing Requirements\n   177→\n   178→- [x] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n   179→- [x] Integration tests for cross-module interactions\n   180→- [x] Coverage target: 100%\n   181→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   182→\n   183→## Dev Agent Record\n   184→\n   185→### Agent Model Used\n   186→\n   187→Claude Opus 4.6 (1M context)\n   188→\n   189→### Debug Log References\n   190→\n   191→### Completion Notes List\n   192→\n   193→- Implemented multi-stage Dockerfile generation in `dockerfile-template.ts` (149 → ~220 lines, under 300 limit)\n   194→- Signature accepts `string | null | StackDetection[]` with runtime `Array.isArray()` detection\n   195→- Added `nodejsBuildStage()`, `pythonBuildStage()`, `rustBuildStage()` for multi-stage build content\n   196→- Added `multiStageTemplate()` composing build stages + shared `debian:bookworm-slim` runtime\n   197→- Single-stack `StackDetection[]` (length=1) delegates to existing single-stack templates — byte-identical output confirmed by tests\n   198→- `DockerfileTemplateResult` now includes `stacks: string[]` alongside `stack: string`\n   199→- Updated `init-project.ts` to pass `allStacks` instead of `stack` to `generateDockerfileTemplate()`\n   200→- Updated `types.ts` to add optional `stacks` field to dockerfile result\n   201→- Validator already handled multi-stage correctly (iterates all FROM lines, checks for pinned tags) — no changes needed\n   202→- No changes needed to `index.ts` — no new exports required\n   203→- 20 new tests added, 3129 total tests pass (was 3109), zero regressions\n   204→- 100% statement/function/line coverage on `dockerfile-template.ts`\n   205→\n   206→### File List\n   207→\n   208→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-template.ts` — Updated: multi-stage composition, signature change, new build-stage functions\n   209→- `src/modules/infra/init-project.ts` — Updated: pass `allStacks` to `generateDockerfileTemplate()`, add `stacks` to result\n   210→- `src/modules/infra/types.ts` — Updated: added `stacks?: string[]` to dockerfile result type\n   211→- `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-template.test.ts` — Updated: 20 new multi-stage tests\n   212→\n   213→## Change Log\n   214→\n   215→- 2026-03-23: Story 9-4 implemented — multi-stage Dockerfile generation with backward-compatible API, 20 new tests, zero regressions\n   216→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017jkzWrDhmfYHNpbYuB4NZk","session_id":"e8d3a9d7-303a-4d24-9a07-31410ec5